column40: Developing fresh fish products from underexploited species. This project aims to attract consumers’ attention towards alternative fish species. The project will build up close cooperation between several actors, e.g. local fishermen and fish refineries in order to guarantee the supply of fish. It will also look at product development and the development of recipes of alternative fish species, as well as offering training for staff in institutional kitchens and for entrepreneurs within fisheries and fish processing businesses.

Diversifying fisheries products: making use of fish skin to make leather. This project involves an awareness raising campaign around the possible uses of fish skin leather, including the production of handbags, lampshades and belts. It also offers training for fishermen, their families and other interested members of the community in tanning and the design and production of fish skin products.

This example relates to the Fisheries Local Action Group 'FLAG' strategy for the Ostrobothnian coastline in the Baltic Sea, which covers a 250-km long stretch of coastline on the west coast of Finland. A project was proposed to develop fresh fish products from underexploited species. It aimed to build ties among several actors (e.g. fishers and fish processing businesses), promote new fish products and recipes, and offer training opportunities for existing staff and entrepeneurs.

A second project proposed under the same FLAG strategy for the Ostrobothnian coastline is to diversify fisheries products: 'making use of fish skin to make leather'. The first phase involved an awareness raising campaign around the possible uses of fish skin leather, including the production of handbags, lampshades and belts. It also offered training for fishers, their families and other interested members of the community in tanning and the design and production of fish skin products.

column40: A third project proposed under this same FLAG strategy was to make winter fishing in the region profitable again. The project aimed to develop net and fyke net fishing of whitefish, perch, northern pike, and burbot as well as seine-fishing of Baltic herring under the ice. A key objective was to supply fresh fish to local consumers during winter, whilst improving the financial standing and working conditions of individual fishers. The project will also build up networks between individual fishers and regions.
